  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Lying Awake at Night with Thoughts of Scholar Saha
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My old friend has risen to the azure clouds above,
    while I, grown old, sing alone by yellow chrysanthemums.
    Though a high canopy cannot fit in this narrow alley,
    still the wine cup shall not abandon my new verses.

    A year's autumn rapture wears the colors of the southern hills,
    and in the solitary night, my melancholy heart clings to the waning moon.
    The wandering geese seem to know my loneliness,
    their few cries fading into the vast and empty sky.
  footnotes:
    - The 'azure clouds' (青雲) is a classical image for high official position and worldly success.
    - The contrast between the friend's elevated status and the speaker's humble circumstances frames the poem's meditation on separation and abandonment.
    - The yellow chrysanthemum carries associations with solitude, virtue in obscurity, and the passing of time.
    - The 'wine cup' and 'new verses' suggest the speaker's consolation through poetry and contemplation despite their reduced circumstances.
